Dedicated to Anna Capoccetta (the girl in my cover photo painting my portrait)

"Vincent" (sometimes called "Starry, Starry Night") was written by Don McLean and released as a single on June 17, 1971. It was then released on his second album American Pie on October 24, 1971. (This video was filmed only a few months after the release of the album.)

"Vincent" is about the painter Vincent van Gogh. The lyrics, "Starry, starry night" refer to van Gogh's painting "The Starry Night" which is seen in the beginning of this video. The song also describes other works by van Gogh. Art imitating art...

The song was a #1 hit on the UK Singles Chart, #12 on the Billboard Hot 100, and #2 on the Billboard Easy Listening chart. Billboard ranked it as the #94 song for 1972.

The album American Pie was #1 on the Billboard 200 chart sporting two #1 singles including "American Pie" (the only song I know of that is longer than the theme to Gilligan's Island) which was #1 on the Billboard Hot 100 for four weeks in 1972 and #2 in the UK. In 2002, the song "American Pie" was inducted into the Grammy Hall of Fame. The album was listed in the book "1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die."

Don McLean was inaugurated into the Songwriters Hall of Fame in 2004, and in 2012, he won the BBC Radio 2 Folk Awards Lifetime Achievement Award.
